9cc0603b-d117-44dd-9590-0825f56ec451.04d37a4f-d9ea-4653-8de9-19df1e4b5a65.description=This flow detects the operating system that is running on the specified host. Inputs\: host - The hostname or IP address of the target machine. port - The port number used for ssh connection. Default value\: 22 username - The username to connect to the target machine. password - The password to connect to the target machine. timeout - The timeout in seconds for remote and local execution calls that the operation makes. portDetectionRules - port rules in JSON format based on wich the operating system name will be determinate in case ssh connection fails on unix based hosts and Nmap command fail to determine the OS for Windows hosts. This input must respect the format from the example below or it won't be used. nmapArguments - The arguments used in nmap command in order to detect te operating system. Default value\: nmap -sS -sU -O -Pn --top-ports 20 Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the output of a "uname -a; uname -m; domainname" for Unix based hosts, and the result of a Nmap command "nmap -sS -sU -O -Pn --top-ports 20" for a Windows host. returnCode - The return code of the operation. Valid values\: 32 for a Windows operating system, 18 for Linux, 19 for Solaris, 20 for other operating system, -1 for failure. osName - The completely returned string of the OS name. For Windows target host, this will be an heuristic result. Example\: Microsoft Windows 7, Windows Server 2012, or Windows 8.1 Update 1 version - The operating systems version. For Unix systems, this result contains the kernel release version. For Windows systems, this will be empty. hostName - The host name that the remote computer reports for itself. osArchitecture - The operating system architecture. For Windows systems, this will be empty. Examples\: x86_64 for Linux, i86pc for Solaris fqdn - The fully qualified domain name (FQDN) of the target machine. For Windows systems, this will be empty. Responses\: windows - The operating system is Windows. linux - The operating system is Linux. solaris - The operating system is Solaris. other - Other operating system. failure - The operating system on the remote host could not be detected. Notes\: 1. This operation uses Nmap ("Network Mapper") for Windows target machine, an open source tool for network exploration and security auditing. Nmap must be installed on source machine (Studio/Central/RAS) from http\://nmap.org. 2. The Nmap OS detection is heuristic, based on the TCP/IP stack fingerprinting and network traffic. Nmap sends a series of TCP and UDP packets to the remote host and examines practically every bit in the responses. After performing dozens of tests such as TCP ISN sampling, TCP options support and ordering, IP ID sampling, and the initial window size check, Nmap compares the results to its nmap-os-db database of more than 2,600 known OS fingerprints and prints out the OS details if there is a match. When Nmap performs OS detection against a target and fails to find a perfect match, it usually repeats the attempt. By default, Nmap tries five times if conditions are favorable for OS fingerprint submission, and twice when conditions aren't so good. 3. For Windows RAS, the Operations Orchestration Central/RAS service must be run with Administrator priviledges. 4. portDetectionRules example\: { "Windows"\: { "port_rules"\:[ { "open"\:["135", "445"] }, { "close"\:"22", "open"\:"3389" }, { "open"\:"1002" } ] }, "Unix"\: { "port_rules"\: [ { "open"\:"22" }, { "open"\:"514", "close"\:"135" } ] }, "Other"\:"default" } This example is intended only for undersanding all capabilities for the new input. In case os detector fails with nmap command and with ssh connection this input will be used as follows\: It will try the first rule. For this example if ports 135 and 445 are opened the operation will assume it's a Windows. If one of them is closed it will check the second rule which check if port 22 is closed and 3389 is open. If the second rule is true it will asume the os is still a windows. If not it will check the 3'rd rule and so on. If all rules for the first os fail the rules from the second os will be checked in order. You can define as many responses as you want "Windows", "Unix", "Linux", "Solaris", "AIX", "Other". For each response you must define a array of "port_rules". Each rule can contain one ore many ports to check they are opened and one ore more ports to check if they are closed. All condition from one rule must be ment in order for the operation to return the desired result. You can also add a default result. If all rules checks failed the operation will not fail and will return the default output. It is recomanded the default rule to be the last one. Otherwise operation won't reach the rules after default because default always returns true. 9cc0603b-d117-44dd-9590-0825f56ec451.4ba0a1e2-6fa1-41c0-8aef-8ab51b1332ec.description=
 
This operation reads the content of a file. The operation can be used to read the entire file content in one step or to iterate the file line by line.

Inputs\:
    source - The full path and filename of the file to be read. A UNC path can be supported as the source file path.
    filter -  Regular expression filter to be applied to each line (leave blank for no filter). If this filter is not blank, all rows that contain the filter string will be returned. If no match is found, no lines will be returned.
    store - Whether to store results in the session for retrieval. If "store" is set to true, then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then subsequent calls to the operation results in the next line being returned.  If set to "false", the file will be iterated and in any iteration the number of remaining lines that matched the "filter" will be returned.
Valid values \: true, false
    delimiter - If specified, the entire content of the file  will be read, the specified value will be used as a delimiter between the rows and  the resulting content will be returned. If left blank, the next row will be returned for each subsequent call. 
    user - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host when reading.
    password - Password for the user.
    eofReset -  If set to true, after the No More response has been returned once, the operation will restart reading the file from the beginning on the next call.
Valid values\: true, false
    characterSet - The character set of the file to read from. For invalid or empty input value the default encoding will be used. 
Valid values\: UTF-8, UTF-16 and UTF-32 
Default value\: UTF-8

Responses\:
    more lines - More lines are available to be read in the session.
    no more lines - No lines are available for reading in the session.
    failure - If something went wrong. 

Results\:
    returnCode - This is the primary output. It is 0 if the operation completed successfully  (or if more rows are available when iterate is set to true), 1 if no more items (if iterate is set to true) and -1 in case of failure. 
    COUNT- The number of lines that matched the filter, or if no filter specified, the total lines read (if iterate is false, or delimiter is not null). Otherwise, it returns the number of lines remaining in the session. This result is only returned in line-by-line mode.
    returnResult - Each row by turn (if iterate is true and delimiter is blank) or all rows separated by the delimiter (if iterate is true and delimiter is not blank).
    exception - An exception message if the operation fails.

Note\:
1. If you are using UTF-8 special characters(for example japanese characters), please ensure that your file is encoded in UTF-8 and not in ANSI wich is the default file encoding in windows when you are creating a new file.
2. The "filter" and "eofReset" fields are taken into consideration only if iterate is set to true. Otherwise, they have no impact on the result.
3. If i"store" is set to "true" and "delimiter" is not null, the entire file may or may not still be fully read at once, depending on size. 
4. If "store" is set to "true", then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then, subsequent calls to the operation, result in the next line being returned.

Examples\:
    The following examples are used to illustrate the behavior of the operation for three specific use cases. For these examples, the operation will use as the input source a file called "example.txt", with the absolute path "C\:\Program Files\example.txt" and the following content\:
        "line1
         line2
         line3
         line4"
1. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "store" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is not left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        store\: true
        delimiter\: ,
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will have the following value\: line1,line2,line3,line4
2. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "store" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        store\: true
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the file will be iterated row by row in four subsequent calls. At each call, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will contain the value of one line from the file, in the same order as they are found in the source file (i.e. line1, line2, lin3, line4). 
3. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "store" input field is set to "false" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:       
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: false
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, all matching lines will be iterated and the "returnResult" field will contain, at each iteration, the number of lines remaining to be iterated (i.e\: 4, 3, 2, 1).
9cc0603b-d117-44dd-9590-0825f56ec451.4cdfa8ea-a41e-46d9-bbd4-cf071d99ff8e.description=
Runs a command and allows the user to specify that it runs locally (in this case no port should be specified), via ssh, Global Shell, ROSH, Telnet, or RSH.

Inputs\:
    host - The hostname or ip address.
    port - The port number for connecting to the host.
    username - The username to connect as.
    password - The password of the user. If using a private key file, this will be used as the passphrase for the file.
    protocol - The protocol used to run the command.
Valid values\: ssh, ROSH, Telnet, GlobalShell, RSH, local, WMI, NASConnectTelnet, HPOM, REXEC
    timeout - The time in seconds for protocol->WMI and in milliseconds for others to wait for the command to complete. After the timeout has expired the remote process and all child processes will be terminated. Increase its value if you are getting incomplete output results or timeout. 
Default value\: 600 seconds for protocol->WMI , 90000 milliseconds for other protocols
    command - The command to execute.
    arguments - The arguments to pass to the command.
    environment - Specifies environment variables/values that need to be defined when running command.
    startDir - The path to the starting directory.
    pty - Whether to use pty (used by ssh, GlobalShell).
Valid values\: True, False
Default value\: False
    privateKeyFile - The absolute path to the private key file for remote host.
    sasHost - The host we want to run the ROSH command on.
    sasHostUsername - The username used to run the ROSH command on sasHost.
    usernamePrompt - The prompt that when seen should send the username. This is only used by the Telnet protocol. When used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is 'NAS Login\:'.
    passwordPrompt - The prompt that when given should send the password. This is only used by the Telnet protocol. When used by the NASConnectTelnet protocol, the default value is 'Password\:'.
    outputPath - The network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified, it points to '\\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible', you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default, the path will have to be changed on Windows 2000 systems.
    nasDevice - The NAS device to run the command on when using the NASConnect protocol.
    nasDeviceConsoleMode - The NAS device console mode used to run the command scripts that run the command on the given NAS device. If this input is empty, command scripts are not used, and the connection to the NAS device and the command are issued directly in the console. This is not recommended, since its error handling capabilities are limited and it might result in success even when the command fails to execute. The values for this input can be found in the NAS web interface, as a drop-down list when a new command script is created (ex. Cisco IOS enable).
    hpomNode - The node on which the command is to be executed.
    hpomProtocol - The protocol to communicate with HPOM.
Valid values\: http, https
    characterSet - The characterSet name for stream encoding and decoding between the RAS and target machine. 
Examples\: SJIS, EUC-JP, UTF-8
Default value\: UTF-8 (used by ssh, GlobalShell, Telnet, RSH, REXEC)

Hidden Inputs\:
    useDelegation - This input only applies to the WMI protocol. If set to "true" the operation will use the 'Delegate' impersonation level and the 'Kerberos' authentication protocol. If 'false', empty or missing the operation will use 'Impersonate' for the impersonation level and the default authentication protocol (which is is NTLM).
Values\: true, false
Default\: false

Responses\:
    success - The command was executed successfully.
    failure - The command could not be executed.

Extra Results\:
    stdErr - The STDERR of the command.
    stdOut - The STDOUT of the command.

Note\:
Telnet protocol - Since telnet is not a remote execution protocol but a shell protocol, the response will always be successful if the command was executed in the remote shell.  The return code of the specified command cannot be determined in this protocol.  If you must use the telnet protocol with this operation besure to check the command results. Consider using ssh or rexec protocol instead.
REXEC protocol does not support an IPv6 address as host. The rexec server (rexecd daemon) does not accept IPv6 incoming connections.
9cc0603b-d117-44dd-9590-0825f56ec451.5757788a-706d-4698-9e75-1fa7c3368876.description=
Writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file,  append extra lines to it or even create a new file.

Input Parameters\:
file                - Full path to file (can be a UNC path, will attempt to create directory structure). If the file does not exist it is created first.
contents        - The contents to write to the file. Contents can have a new line delimiter which is also given as input to the operation, but it is optional. Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter.
user              - Username to use for thread impersonation on the RAS host for this operation.
password      - Password for the user.
delimiter       - Specifies the newline delimiter (\n, \r\n, etc) that is used for the "contents" input.
overwrite      - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. By default, the used value is true. Accepted values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten.
characterSet - The character encoding used to write to the file. The default is UTF-8. Example values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE,  ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc.

Responses\:
success - The contents were written to the file.
failure - The operation did not succeed in writing the contents to file.
